# PL/SQL Package Standards

## 1. Always Use Packages
Never build standalone functions or procedures. All PL/SQL logic must be in a package (`*_api` or `*_utils`).

## 2. Variable & Parameter Prefixes
- Local Variables: `l_`
- Parameters: `p_`
- Output Parameters: `o_`
- In/Out Parameters: `io_`
- Global Variables: `g_`
- Scope Constant: `gc_scope_prefix`

## 3. Use %type References
Prefer anchored declarations (`table.column%type`) over hardcoded data types (like `varchar2(100)` or `number`).

```plsql
procedure update_ticket(
    p_ticket_id   in tf_tickets.ticket_id%type
  , p_description in tf_tickets.description%type
)
```

## 4. Multi-line Procedure Calls
- Opening `(` on same line as call.
- First parameter on next line, indented **2 spaces**.
- Use leading commas, vertically align arrows `=>`.
- Closing `);` aligned with the parameters (2-space indent).

```plsql
l_rest_response := apex_web_service.make_rest_request(
    p_url         => gc_api_url
  , p_http_method => 'GET'
);
```

## 5. Documentation Templates
Use JavaDoc-style comments on public procedures/functions.
- `@author [Name]`
- `@created [Month DD, YYYY]`
- `@param [name] [desc]`
- `@return [type] [desc]`

## 6. Instrumentation
Always use `logger`. Start/End logging in every procedure, append params, log exceptions.
